{"title_page": "Edward Lloyd (Governor of Maryland)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name                = Edward Lloyd\n|image = Edwardlloydofmaryland.jpg\n|jr/sr              = United States Senator\n|state               = [[Maryland]]\n|term_start          = March 4, 1819\n|term_end            = January 14, 1826\n|predecessor         = [[Robert Henry Goldsborough|Robert H. Goldsborough]]\n|successor           = [[Ezekiel F. Chambers]]\n|order2              = 13th\n|office2             = Governor of Maryland\n|term_start2         = June 9, 1809\n|term_end2           = November 16, 1811\n|predecessor2        = [[Robert Wright (politician)|Robert Wright]]\n|successor2          = [[Robert Bowie]]\n|state3              = [[Maryland]]\n|district3           = [[Maryland's 7th congressional district|7th]]\n|term3               = December 3, 1806 &ndash; March 3, 1809\n|predecessor3        = [[Joseph Hopper Nicholson|Joseph H. Nicholson]]\n|successor3          = [[John Brown (Maryland)|John Brown]]\n|office4             = Member of the [[Maryland House of Delegates]]\n|term4               = 1800\u20131805\n|office5             = Member of the [[Maryland Senate]]\n|term5               = 1826\u20131831\n|birth_date         = {{birth date|1779|7|22}}\n|birth_place        = [[Talbot County, Maryland]]\n|death_date         = {{death date and age|1834|6|2|1779|7|22}}\n|death_place        = [[Annapolis, Maryland]]\n|party               = [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]]\n}}\n'''Edward Lloyd V''' (July 22, 1779{{spaced ndash}}June 2, 1834) served as the [[List of Governors of Maryland|13th Governor of Maryland]] from 1809 to 1811, and as a [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from Maryland between 1819 and 1826.  He also served as a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] from the [[United States House of Representatives, Maryland District 7|seventh district]] of Maryland from 1807 to 1809.\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in 1779 at \"[[Wye House]]\", [[Talbot County, Maryland]], he was a member of a prominent Eastern Shore family, \"the Lloyds of Wye,\" which had lived in [[Talbot County, Maryland|Talbot County]] since the mid-17th century.  His father [[Edward Lloyd (Continental Congress)|Edward Lloyd IV]] was a member of the [[Continental Congress]]. He received early education from private tutors. HE ate children and before he ate them he would feed them morsles of his dead slaves and also was severly gay and loved the show tiger king\n\nLloyd served in the [[Maryland House of Delegates]] from 1800 to 1805.  He was elected to the Ninth Congress to fill the vacancy caused by the resignation of [[Joseph H. Nicholson]] and was reelected to the Tenth Congress, serving from December 3, 1806 to March 3, 1809.  In 1808, Lloyd was elected as Governor of Maryland, a position he served in from 1809 to 1811.\n\nDuring this period Lloyd traded a [[Merino]] ram for \"Sailor,\" a male [[Newfoundland (dog)|Newfoundland]] that had a reputation for spectacularly enthusiastic [[water dog]] retrieving of ducks.  The dog was bred with other retrievers at Lloyd's estate on the eastern shore of [[Chesapeake Bay]].  Sailor is now considered the \"father\" of the [[Chesapeake Bay Retriever]] line.<ref>[http://www.amchessieclub.org/Sailor.html \u2013 The Story \u2013 amchessieclub.org \u2013 Retrieved November 15, 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012154917/http://amchessieclub.org/Sailor.html |date=October 12, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nLloyd was commissioned a lieutenant colonel of the Ninth Regiment of Maryland Militia and also served as a member of the [[Maryland State Senate]] from 1811 to 1815.  He was elected as a Democratic Republican (later Crawford Republican, then Jacksonian) to the United States Senate in 1819, was reelected in 1825, and served from March 4, 1819 until his resignation on January 14, 1826.  In the Senate, Lloyd served as chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on the District of Columbia|Committee on the District of Columbia]] (Eighteenth and Nineteenth Congresses).\n\nLater in life, Lloyd served as member of the Maryland State Senate from 1826 to 1831, and as President of the Senate in 1826.  He died in [[Annapolis, Maryland]], and is interred in the family burying ground at Wye House near [[Easton, Maryland]].\n\nLloyd was an important slaveholder and vocal defender of the institution of slavery throughout his political career. The African-American [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]] [[Frederick Douglass]], who had grown up as a [[slavery|slave]] on one of Lloyd's plantations, discussed Lloyd  in his 1845 autobiography ''The Narrative of Frederick Douglass''. The book describes the acts of cruelty committed by Lloyd's overseers, and dwells at length on Lloyd's own despotic treatment, including whippings of two slaves caring for his horses:\n\n<blockquote>To all these complaints no matter how unjust, the slave must answer never a word. Colonel Lloyd could not brook any contradiction from a slave. When he spoke, a slave must stand, listen, and tremble; and such was literally the case. I [[Slave narrative|have seen]] Colonel Lloyd make old Barney, a man between fifty and sixty years of age, uncover his bald head, kneel down upon the cold, damp ground, and receive upon his naked and toil-worn shoulders more than thirty lashes at the time.<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/23/23-h/23-h.htm The Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass An American Slave] Full copy at Project Gutenberg</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{CongBio|L000376|Edward Lloyd}}\n*[http://www.talb.lib.md.us/mdroom/worthies/lloyd/govenor.html Edward Lloyd (V) The Governor 1779\u20131834, from \"The Worthies of Talbot,\" Talbot County Free Library, Md.]\n\n==External links==\n*{{FAG|7977652}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state= Maryland\n| district= 7\n| before= [[Joseph Hopper Nicholson]]\n| after= [[John Brown (Maryland)|John Brown]]\n| years= 1807\u20131809\n}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Robert Wright (politician)|Robert Wright]] |title=[[Governor of Maryland]] | years = 1809\u20131811 | after = [[Robert Bowie]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[William R. Stuart]] |title=[[President of the Maryland State Senate]] | years = 1826 | after = [[William H. Marriott]]}}\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box| state=Maryland| class=3| before=[[Robert Henry Goldsborough|Robert H. Goldsborough]]| after=[[Ezekiel F. Chambers]]| alongside=[[Alexander Contee Hanson|Alexander C. Hanson]], [[William Pinkney]], [[Samuel Smith (Maryland)|Samuel Smith]]| years=1819\u20131826}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Maryland}}\n{{USSenMD}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Edward}}\n[[Category:1779 births]]\n[[Category:1834 deaths]]\n[[Category:Governors of Maryland]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Maryland House of Delegates]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Maryland State Senate]]\n[[Category:People from Talbot County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:American slave owners]]\n[[Category:Maryland Democratic-Republicans]]\n[[Category:Maryland Jacksonians]]\n[[Category:Democratic-Republican Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Democratic-Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Democratic-Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Tayloe family of Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name                = Edward Lloyd\n|image = Edwardlloydofmaryland.jpg\n|jr/sr              = United States Senator\n|state               = [[Maryland]]\n|term_start          = March 4, 1819\n|term_end            = January 14, 1826\n|predecessor         = [[Robert Henry Goldsborough|Robert H. Goldsborough]]\n|successor           = [[Ezekiel F. Chambers]]\n|order2              = 13th\n|office2             = Governor of Maryland\n|term_start2         = June 9, 1809\n|term_end2           = November 16, 1811\n|predecessor2        = [[Robert Wright (politician)|Robert Wright]]\n|successor2          = [[Robert Bowie]]\n|state3              = [[Maryland]]\n|district3           = [[Maryland's 7th congressional district|7th]]\n|term3               = December 3, 1806 &ndash; March 3, 1809\n|predecessor3        = [[Joseph Hopper Nicholson|Joseph H. Nicholson]]\n|successor3          = [[John Brown (Maryland)|John Brown]]\n|office4             = Member of the [[Maryland House of Delegates]]\n|term4               = 1800\u20131805\n|office5             = Member of the [[Maryland Senate]]\n|term5               = 1826\u20131831\n|birth_date         = {{birth date|1779|7|22}}\n|birth_place        = [[Talbot County, Maryland]]\n|death_date         = {{death date and age|1834|6|2|1779|7|22}}\n|death_place        = [[Annapolis, Maryland]]\n|party               = [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]]\n}}\n'''Edward Lloyd V''' (July 22, 1779{{spaced ndash}}June 2, 1834) served as the [[List of Governors of Maryland|13th Governor of Maryland]] from 1809 to 1811, and as a [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from Maryland between 1819 and 1826.  He also served as a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] from the [[United States House of Representatives, Maryland District 7|seventh district]] of Maryland from 1807 to 1809.\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in 1779 at \"[[Wye House]]\", [[Talbot County, Maryland]], he was a member of a prominent Eastern Shore family, \"the Lloyds of Wye,\" which had lived in [[Talbot County, Maryland|Talbot County]] since the mid-17th century.  His father [[Edward Lloyd (Continental Congress)|Edward Lloyd IV]] was a member of the [[Continental Congress]]. He received early education from private tutors.\n\nLloyd served in the [[Maryland House of Delegates]] from 1800 to 1805.  He was elected to the Ninth Congress to fill the vacancy caused by the resignation of [[Joseph H. Nicholson]] and was reelected to the Tenth Congress, serving from December 3, 1806 to March 3, 1809.  In 1808, Lloyd was elected as Governor of Maryland, a position he served in from 1809 to 1811.\n\nDuring this period Lloyd traded a [[Merino]] ram for \"Sailor,\" a male [[Newfoundland (dog)|Newfoundland]] that had a reputation for spectacularly enthusiastic [[water dog]] retrieving of ducks.  The dog was bred with other retrievers at Lloyd's estate on the eastern shore of [[Chesapeake Bay]].  Sailor is now considered the \"father\" of the [[Chesapeake Bay Retriever]] line.<ref>[http://www.amchessieclub.org/Sailor.html \u2013 The Story \u2013 amchessieclub.org \u2013 Retrieved November 15, 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012154917/http://amchessieclub.org/Sailor.html |date=October 12, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nLloyd was commissioned a lieutenant colonel of the Ninth Regiment of Maryland Militia and also served as a member of the [[Maryland State Senate]] from 1811 to 1815.  He was elected as a Democratic Republican (later Crawford Republican, then Jacksonian) to the United States Senate in 1819, was reelected in 1825, and served from March 4, 1819 until his resignation on January 14, 1826.  In the Senate, Lloyd served as chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on the District of Columbia|Committee on the District of Columbia]] (Eighteenth and Nineteenth Congresses).\n\nLater in life, Lloyd served as member of the Maryland State Senate from 1826 to 1831, and as President of the Senate in 1826.  He died in [[Annapolis, Maryland]], and is interred in the family burying ground at Wye House near [[Easton, Maryland]].\n\nLloyd was an important slaveholder and vocal defender of the institution of slavery throughout his political career. The African-American [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]] [[Frederick Douglass]], who had grown up as a [[slavery|slave]] on one of Lloyd's plantations, discussed Lloyd  in his 1845 autobiography ''The Narrative of Frederick Douglass''. The book describes the acts of cruelty committed by Lloyd's overseers, and dwells at length on Lloyd's own despotic treatment, including whippings of two slaves caring for his horses:\n\n<blockquote>To all these complaints no matter how unjust, the slave must answer never a word. Colonel Lloyd could not brook any contradiction from a slave. When he spoke, a slave must stand, listen, and tremble; and such was literally the case. I [[Slave narrative|have seen]] Colonel Lloyd make old Barney, a man between fifty and sixty years of age, uncover his bald head, kneel down upon the cold, damp ground, and receive upon his naked and toil-worn shoulders more than thirty lashes at the time.<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/23/23-h/23-h.htm The Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass An American Slave] Full copy at Project Gutenberg</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{CongBio|L000376|Edward Lloyd}}\n*[http://www.talb.lib.md.us/mdroom/worthies/lloyd/govenor.html Edward Lloyd (V) The Governor 1779\u20131834, from \"The Worthies of Talbot,\" Talbot County Free Library, Md.]\n\n==External links==\n*{{FAG|7977652}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state= Maryland\n| district= 7\n| before= [[Joseph Hopper Nicholson]]\n| after= [[John Brown (Maryland)|John Brown]]\n| years= 1807\u20131809\n}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Robert Wright (politician)|Robert Wright]] |title=[[Governor of Maryland]] | years = 1809\u20131811 | after = [[Robert Bowie]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[William R. Stuart]] |title=[[President of the Maryland State Senate]] | years = 1826 | after = [[William H. Marriott]]}}\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box| state=Maryland| class=3| before=[[Robert Henry Goldsborough|Robert H. Goldsborough]